The most important of the many cases of police brutality reported in southern California 1989-1992, was the beating of Rodney King by four Los Angeles officers on March 3, 1991.
An investigating commission outlined steps for improvement of the police department and called for the resignation of Chief Gates.
Gates did not resign until the following year after the acquittal of the four officers caused massive rioting.
Other cases of police brutality arose in Minneapolis, Chicago and Kansas City.
Operation Rescue claimed that its non-violent anti-abortion demonstrators were seriously injured by excessive police tactics in more than 50 cities.